Good morning,

On yesterday=E2=80=99s episode of Dithering ( https://dithering.fm/ ) , Joh=
n and I discussed former Intel CEO Pat Gelsinger=E2=80=99s resignation/firi=
ng.

On to the Update:

AWS re:Invent
-------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-12-03/amazon-=
unveils-chip-clusters-with-five-times-power-for-anthropic ) :

Amazon.com Inc. is ramping up its artificial intelligence offerings, rollin=
g out powerful new chip arrays and a large language model it says can compe=
te with leading rivals. The Seattle-based company is stringing together hun=
dreds of thousands of its Trainium2 semiconductors into clusters that will =
make it easier for partner Anthropic to train the large language models req=
uired for generative AI and other machine learning tasks. The new arrays wi=
ll quintuple the startup=E2=80=99s current processing power, Amazon said. A=
mazon Web Services, the cloud services division, began offering its latest =
chips to customers on Tuesday, the company said at its annual re:Invent con=
ference.

Andy Jassy, marking his first appearance at the trade show since becoming A=
mazon=E2=80=99s chief executive officer in 2021, introduced the new models =
=E2=80=94 called Nova. Capable of generating text, images and video, they r=
epresent Amazon=E2=80=99s latest effort to compete with OpenAI and other bu=
ilders of the large language models that power chatbots and other generativ=
e AI tools. AWS, the largest seller of rented computing power, runs many of=
 the servers that other companies rent to train artificial intelligence app=
lications. AWS also makes models built by other companies, including Anthro=
pic=E2=80=99s Claude and Meta Platforms Inc.=E2=80=99s Llama, available to =
AWS customers. But the company has yet to produce a large language model wi=
dely seen as competitive with OpenAI=E2=80=99s most advanced GPT models.

I=E2=80=99ll get to the Jassy segment of the keynote ( https://www.youtube.=
com/watch?v=3DLY7m5LQliAo ) in a moment; in that I am following the lead of=
 AWS CEO Matt Garman, who conducted most of the keynote and, while talking =
about traditional AWS topics like processors and databases, laid the ground=
work for Jassy. For example, Garman started out by talking about all of the=
 compute options AWS offered:

( https://videopress.com/embed/EDhtSiZQ?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmetadata )

The good news is lots of customers love EC2 too. Why? Because EC2 has more =
options, more instances, and more capabilities, and it helps you find the e=
xact right performance for the workload that you need. In fact, at this poi=
nt, we=E2=80=99ve grown to where EC2 has 850 different instance types acros=
s 126 different families. What that means is you can always find the exact =
right instance type for the workload that you need.

Garman then spent some time explaining how this instance variety was possib=
le due to Nitro, the custom networking and hypervisor management chip that =
sits alongside every AWS server:

( https://videopress.com/embed/HzZRZbeF?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmetadata )

So one question I get from a lot of customers is, =E2=80=9CHow do you possi=
bly sustain that level of innovation? What allows you to deliver so much?=
=E2=80=9D One of the answers to that is Nitro. Nitro is our AWS virtualizat=
ion system. Effectively, what we did is we designed a custom chip that offl=
oads all of the virtualization for networking, for storage, and for compute=
, off into this separate Nitro card system. What that allows us to do is it=
 allows us to deliver bare metal performance, it allows us to deliver unpar=
alleled security and isolation for customers that unmatched anywhere in the=
 cloud, but an interesting other benefit of Nitro is that it gives us a ton=
 of flexibility. When we move all of the virtualization off into this Nitro=
 system separately, it allows us to innovate independently, so we don=E2=80=
=99t have to redo the virtualization stack every time we have a new instanc=
e type. We can simply develop a great new server and then develop the virtu=
alization stack independently and put them together. That allows us to move=
 much faster, and it=E2=80=99s interesting: Nitro has been one of the keys =
that has really unlocked the speed of innovation in compute at AWS.

Garman then explained how Nitro started Amazon down the path to building it=
s own silicon, including Graviton, its ARM-based alternative to Intel and A=
MD, which Garman said offers 40% better price performance and 60% better en=
ergy utilization than x86. Garman also said that the amount of Graviton com=
pute on AWS today exceeds the total amount of compute on the service in 201=
9 when Graviton launched.

This, then, led to the discussion of Trainium2, Amazon=E2=80=99s own AI chi=
p, which is now generally available, along with the announcement that Train=
ium3 is coming next year. The promise sounded familiar: 30-40% better price=
 performance than current generation GPU-based instances (i.e. Nvidia Hoppe=
r). Of course AWS will be offering Nvidia=E2=80=99s new Blackwell GPUs as w=
ell.

Nova and Model Choice
---------------------

Jump forward to Jassy=E2=80=99s appearance, which was framed as a discussio=
n of how Amazon is using generative AI internally. After running through a =
number of examples of Amazon services, Jassy had this to say:

( https://videopress.com/embed/QzGShTda?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmetadata )

These are, by the way, just a few of the almost 1,000 generative AI applica=
tions that we are either building or have built inside of Amazon, and we ha=
ve obviously learned a lot of lessons along the way, and I=E2=80=99d share =
a few of those with you =E2=80=94 just three right now.

First, is that as you get to scale in generative AI applications, the cost =
of compute really matters. All of our generative applications around the wo=
rld, all of us, it=E2=80=99s primarily been built with one chip in that com=
pute, and people are very hungry for better price performance, and that=E2=
=80=99s why people are so excited about Trainium2 as Matt was talking about=
 earlier.

Number two, it=E2=80=99s actually quite difficult to build a really big gen=
erative AI application. You need a good model, but it=E2=80=99s not just th=
e model. In addition to the model, you have to have the right guardrails, y=
ou have to have the right fluency of the messaging, and you have to have th=
e right UI, and you have to have the right latency, or it=E2=80=99s a reall=
y slow, laggy experience, and you have to have the right cost structure. I =
think a lot of times what happens is you build these apps, you use a great =
model, you do a little bit of work, and you think I have a great generative=
 AI app, and it turns out that you are really only about 70% of the way the=
re, and the reality is customers don=E2=80=99t take kindly to apps that hav=
e 30% wonkiness.

And then, the third thing I would say, I have been surprised with all the i=
nternal building inside of Amazon, with the diversity of models being used.=
 We gave our builders freedom to pick what they want to do, and I figured t=
hat almost everybody would end up using Anthropic=E2=80=99s Claude models b=
ecause they=E2=80=99re the very best performing models in the world, and ha=
ve been for the last year or so. And by the way, we have a lot of our inter=
nal builders using Claude. But, they=E2=80=99re also using Llama models. Th=
ey=E2=80=99re also using Mistral models, and they=E2=80=99re also using som=
e of our own models, and they=E2=80=99re also using home-grown models thems=
elves.

So this kind of surprised us, but in some ways, as I think about it, it doe=
sn=E2=80=99t surprise us, because we keep learning the same lesson over and=
 over and over again, which is that there is never going to be one tool to =
rule the world. It=E2=80=99s not the case in databases =E2=80=94 we=E2=80=
=99ve been talking about this for ten years, people use lots of different r=
elational databases or non-relational databases =E2=80=93 it=E2=80=99s not =
the case in analytics. I remember six, seven years ago being on stage, and =
we were talking about how everybody thought that Tensorflow was going to be=
 the one AI framework. We kept saying there are going to be a lot of them, =
and there were, and it turns out that PyTorch ended up being the most popul=
ar one. And the same is going to be true for models. We see this internally=
.

What we=E2=80=99ve noticed is as we=E2=80=99ve been building all these appl=
ications is that our internal builders have been asking for all sorts of th=
ings from our teams that are building models. They want better latency, the=
y want lower costs, they want the ability to do fine-tuning. They want the =
ability to better orchestrate across their different knowledge bases to be =
able to ground their data. They want to take lots of automated orchestrated=
 actions, or what people call agentic behavior. They want better image and =
video. They want a whole bunch of things. We share that feedback with our m=
odel provider partners, and they=E2=80=99re accepted, but they=E2=80=99re b=
usy. You guys want a lot! There=E2=80=99s a lot to do.

And so it=E2=80=99s one of the reasons why we have continued to work on our=
 own frontier models, and those frontier models have made a tremendous amou=
nt of progress over the last four to five months, and we figured if we were=
 finding value out of them, you would probably find value out of them, so I=
=E2=80=99m excited to share and announce the launch of Amazon Nova, which a=
re our new state-of-the-art foundation models that deliver frontier intelli=
gence at industry-leading price performance.

Forgive the long excerpt, but this is maybe the best articulation yet of AW=
S=E2=80=99s AI strategy, which, unsurprisingly, looks a lot like the AWS st=
rategy generally.

First is that bit about choice. Just as AWS offers a huge amount of choice =
in processing or databases, AWS will offer choice in models. Second, while =
I skipped over the Bedrock portion of Garman=E2=80=99s presentation, that i=
s the Nitro in this analogy. Bedrock is AWS=E2=80=99s managed service for m=
odels, and it has features that Jassy listed: fine-tuning, integration acro=
ss knowlege bases, agent orchestration, etc. Third, while Bedrock will offe=
r access to 3rd-party models, just as AWS offers access to third-party chip=
s, the biggest benefit to Amazon itself, and over-time the likely cheapest =
option for 3rd-party developers, will be Amazon=E2=80=99s own offering.

Nova itself seems fine; on LiveBench ( https://livebench.ai/ ) Nova Pro ran=
ks just behind Gemini 1.5 Flash, Llama 3.1 70b, and just ahead of Claude 3.=
5 Haiku and GPT 4o Mini; that=E2=80=99s a fair bit off the pace from Claude=
 3.5 Sonnet, GPT 4o, Gemini 1.5 Pro, and Meta Llama 3.1 405b. It=E2=80=99s =
also much cheaper than Claude=E2=80=99s high-end model (although more expen=
sive that Llama 3.2 90b). The big focus seems to be latency: Jassy emphasiz=
ed its speed, and you=E2=80=99ll note how he called out latency as the firs=
t request from his internal teams.

AI as Commodity
---------------

In March 2023, Dylan Patel at SemiAnalysis wrote an article entitled, Amazo=
n=E2=80=99s Cloud Crisis: How AWS Will Lose the Future of Computing ( https=
://semianalysis.com/2023/03/20/amazons-cloud-crisis-how-aws-will/ ) , where=
 he highlighted Nitro as a brilliant innovation that helped AWS dominate co=
mmodity compute, but a significant limiter on the company=E2=80=99s AI capa=
bilities:

Amazon is installing their 5th generation Nitro which was designed in-house=
. The advantages that Nitro brings from an infrastructure cost perspective =
cannot be understated. It enables much lower costs for Amazon, which can th=
en be passed on to customers, or result in higher margins. With that said, =
Amazon=E2=80=99s Nitro also has some major drawbacks=E2=80=A6

Amazon is actively hampering its efforts in AI clusters. Compute is only pa=
rt of the equation. Networking is the other side and arguably just as impor=
tant. Rather than implement the best networking from Nvidia and/or Broadcom=
, Amazon is using its own Nitro and Elastic Fabric Adaptor (EFA) networking=
. This works well for many workloads, plus it delivers a cost, performance,=
 and security advantage.

There are business, cultural, and security reasons why Amazon will not impl=
ement other networking. The cultural one is important. Nitro and networking=
 SoC=E2=80=99s generally have been Amazon=E2=80=99s biggest cost advantage =
for years. It=E2=80=99s ingrained into their DNA. Even EFA delivers on this=
 too, but they don=E2=80=99t see how new workloads are evolving and that a =
new tier is needed due to the lack of foresight in their internal workload =
and infrastructure teams. Amazon is making a deliberate choice of not adopt=
ing that we believe will bite them in the future.

Patel and company have a new article up this week ( https://semianalysis.co=
m/2024/12/03/amazons-ai-self-sufficiency-trainium2-architecture-networking/=
 ) about Trainium2 and how AWS is building out that big cluster for Anthrop=
ic, including a detailed explanation about the company=E2=80=99s new approa=
ches to both scale-up networking (to increased the number of chips in a ser=
ver) and scale-out networking (to increase cluster size). It will certainly=
 be interesting to see how well that ends up working out for Anthropic and =
the models they will train on AWS=E2=80=99 infrastructure.

At the same time, the Anthropic training cluster felt like the exception to=
 AWS=E2=80=99 approach, not the rule: the emphasis on =E2=80=9Cchoice=E2=80=
=9D in the presentation, first in terms of regular AWS, and then later in t=
erms of AI, is another way to say that the options are, in the end, mere co=
mmodities. Sure, the cutting edge for both inference and especially trainin=
g will be Nvidia, and AWS will offer Nvidia instances (to the extent they f=
it in AWS=E2=80=99 network), but AWS=E2=80=99s bet is that a necessary comp=
onent of generative AI being productized is that models fade in importance.=
 Note this bit from Garman leading up to his Bedrock discussion:

( https://videopress.com/embed/xRDOuuTs?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmetadata )

We talked about wanting this set of building blocks that builders could use=
 to invent anything that they could imagine. We also talked about how many =
of the cases we walked through today, that we=E2=80=99ve redefined how peop=
le thought about these as applications change. Now people=E2=80=99s expecta=
tions are actually changing for applications again with generative AI, and =
increasingly my view is generative AI inference is going to be a core build=
ing block for every single application. In fact, I think generative AI actu=
ally has the potential to transform every single industry, every single com=
pany out there, every single workflow out there, every single user experien=
ce out there=E2=80=A6

This expansive view of generative AI=E2=80=99s importance =E2=80=94 notice =
how Garman put it on the same level as the compute, storage, and database p=
rimitives =E2=80=94 emphasizes the importance of it becoming a commodity, w=
ith commodity-like concerns about price, performance, and flexibility. In o=
ther words, exactly what AWS excels at. To put it another way, AWS=E2=80=99=
s bet is that AI will be important enough that it won=E2=80=99t, in the end=
, be special at all, which is very much Amazon=E2=80=99s sweet spot.

